  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT246-kilavi">ciṟaippuṟam. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Hedge. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT246">
          <l>peruṅkaṭaṟ karaiyatu ciṟuveṇ kākkai</l>
          <l>kaḷiṟṟuccevi yaṉṉa pācaṭai mayakkip</l>
          <l>paṉikkaḻi tuḻavum pāṉāṭ ṭaṉittōr</l>
          <l>tērvantu peyarnta teṉpa vataṟkoṇ</l>
          <l>ṭōru malaikku maṉṉai piṟarum</l>
          <l>piṉṉuviṭu katuppiṉ miṉṉiḻai makaḷi</l>
          <l>riḷaiyaru maṭavaru muḷarē</l>
          <l>yalaiyāt tāyaroṭu naṟpā lōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>A chariot came [and] went, they say,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">solitary, at midday, when the little white crow <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṟu veṇ kākkai</term>: is this a standing phrase to denote a seagull,
            which is a white bird of the seashore, by size, voice and behaviour comparable to the
            crow? T.V.G. explains it as a particular kind of crow to be found on the seaside, which
            has a white spot on its neck.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent3">from the shore of the great sea disturbs the green leaves</l>
          <l rend="indent4">like elephant ears, [and] stirs the misty backwaters.</l>
          <l>There are young and inexperienced</l>
          <l>women with flashing jewels in braids coming loose <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piṉṉu viṭu</term>: what is achieved here by <term xml:lang="ta">
            viṭu-tal</term> ? T.V.G. takes it just as "well-decorated".</note>
          </l>
          <l>– they [have] the better part, with mothers who don't slap [them] –</l>
          <l>and others with mothers who, taking that [as a cause],</l>
          <l rend="indent8">interrogate [and] slap [them]. <note place="foot">How to account for the
            syntax of these four lines? Probably it is best to explain it as a change of word order
            for reasons of emphasis. <term xml:lang="ta">miṉṉiḻai makaḷir</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">piṟar</term> are to be read as the coordinate subjects of <term xml:lang="ta">uḷarē</term> , and <term xml:lang="ta">iḷaiyar</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">maṭavar</term> are subject appositions just to <term xml:lang="ta">
            makaḷir</term> . The last line has to be read as an independent sentence which comments
            on the <term xml:lang="ta">makaḷir</term> . So the piṟar, who logically come second, are
            put in front so as not to interrupt the climactic three-lines description of the <term xml:lang="ta">makaḷir</term> .</note></l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
